Observation Details: *Really cool experience today - a non-birding couple was staring up at a woodpecker, and when I tried to find it I was looking much too far - there was a male Hairy just 5 ft away on a tree right along the trail. It was very confiding, but extremely flighty - moving from tree to tree, tapping on them (appearing to be listening), and then moving to the next tree. After about 3-5 minutes of easy naked eye looks, it flew to a tree where evidently it had already been excavating, as there was a keyhole cavity that was quite fresh.  It reached into the keyhole and started eating ants and possibly a spider/beetle. Soon it started to tap just below the keyhole, and then started peeling the bark off , exposing the fresh wood below. After some more tapping to test out the wood's strength, it starting hammering in earnest, creating a second keyhole cavity connected to the first (all while I was filming). This larger combined keyhole apparently attracted more ants, and it seemed to hit the mother load. It was very patient in waiting for more ants to come. After probably 10-15 minutes of excavating and feasting, and when the ants seemed to dry up, it hitched up to a higher branch, and rubbed it's bill side to side on the branch.

Observation Details: Both females - I have 2 suet feeders about 26 feet apart, one strapped to the trunk of a maple tree and one is a Tail Prop feeder on a pole feeding system.  The woodpecker on the tree, landed on the tree about 25 feet above the ground then backed her way down the tree.  She fed from the bottom of the suet cage.  As she pecked the suet block, some of the suet cake crumbs landed on her chest and she ate them off her chest.  When the flicker flew in, she backed lower down on the trunk and moved to the opposite side of the tree.  Then she hopped/climbed up the trunk and flew off.  The female on the tail prop feeder on the pole got pounded on the head by a Red-Breasted Nuthatch but continued eating.  The nuthatch then starting eating on the opposite side of the feeder. Two other nuthatches and several chickadees flew to/from the feeder while she ate for about 3 &1/2 minutes.  I usually hear her peeping for a few minutes before she flies in, and she continue peeping while she eats.

Observation Details: Visiting our backyard feeder, a male shows its red nape. Notice the white outer tail feathers lack the black baring of the similar but smaller Downy Woodpecker. These two woodpeckers are not each other's closest relatives. Both species exhibit parallel geographic variation with those in Eastern North America having more white spotting on their wings while those in the far West have little or no wing spotting. Thus the two seem to mimic each other across their range. This is sometimes called interspecific social dominance mimicry (Prum, Zool J Linn Soc, 172: 910-941, 2014). However it seems unlikely that this mimicry is driven by "social dominance," but more likely by predator avoidance. One species evolves to look like another to avoid being noticed.

Observation Details: Initially seen and heard in a group of oaks in the parking area at the boat ramp at 7:55am, making very loud clear peek notes, louder and more emphatic than DOWO - attaching audio file.  Was able to see the woodpecker with noticeably longer bill compared  to DOWO.  Before I could get a photo, it flew west.  I followed it to (29.55599, -82.61160), where it continued  making the same loud peek calls every 3-5 seconds.  As soon as I located it again in another group of oaks, it flew north and I lost it.   After a long loop west then north, on my way back I found it again at (29.56231, -82.61271) at 10:40am, again making the same loud peek calls, again in an oak tree.  This was about 0.5 miles north of where I last saw it.  This time I was able to get photos showing the long bill and no barring on outer white tail feathers. It was larger and broader-breasted looking compared to DOWO.  Photos attached.

*Really cool experience today - a non-birding couple was staring up at a woodpecker, and when I tried to find it I was looking much too far - there was a male Hairy just 5 ft away on a tree right along the trail. It was very confiding, but extremely flighty - moving from tree to tree, tapping on them (appearing to be listening), and then moving to the next tree. After about 3-5 minutes of easy naked eye looks, it flew to a tree where evidently it had already been excavating, as there was a keyhole cavity that was quite fresh.  It reached into the keyhole and started eating ants and possibly a spider/beetle. Soon it started to tap just below the keyhole, and then started peeling the bark off , exposing the fresh wood below. After some more tapping to test out the wood's strength, it starting hammering in earnest, creating a second keyhole cavity connected to the first (all while I was filming). This larger combined keyhole apparently attracted more ants, and it seemed to hit the mother load. It was very patient in waiting for more ants to come. After probably 10-15 minutes of excavating and feasting, and when the ants seemed to dry up, it hitched up to a higher branch, and rubbed it's bill side to side on the branch.

This species is rare at this location; the third or fourth record in six years.  Also uncommon to rare anywhere in the valley; typically found in higher elevation forests in this area.  This is the expected subspecies in the area, but subspecies was also confirmed by plumage, including all-white back center, reduced white spotting in wings, etc.  Hairy Woodpecker and Downy Woodpecker seen together in the same tree for great direct comparison, once immediately next to each other.

Yard list first, and the second new yard bird today after a year-plus drought! Nice! The best views I've ever had of a HAWO.  Unbelievably cooperative male on shady trail in the general vicinity of (38.652581,-121.211314) and only a few hundred feet from the parking lot. This area, the first half of shady trail, has been cleared as a fire barrier, and most of the underbrush and quite a few of the trees have been taken out. This created a very similar habitat to other places I've seen HAWO in the foothills. I would guess this bird is presumably here to stay, at least for a while, as it was frequently drumming and and creating tree cavities in at least two locations. It was still present in the same general area four hours later.

While I was watching it, I noticed a squirrel behind the trunk on which it was foraging. At first it roamed around the bird, who was beginning to grow alarmed, stopping its feeding and lifting itself  off the trunk, and looking from side to side. Then in a jerky way, the squirrel approached the woodpecker  who retreated as the rodent came nearer. Finally, the squirrel made a dash at the bird who promptly flitted to another trunk.
